abstract: The usual backing and filling process which is often witnessed between periods of transition in the stock market was again evidence yesterday when prices of the leading stocks rose and fell with much irregularity. abstract: The local board of United States Steamboat Inspectors yesterday exonerated Capt. M.W. abstract: Annie Turner, who on Thursday had gone to visit her sister, Mrs. L. Neassy, at her home, 325 Garden Street, Hoboken, was shot four times yesterday noon by Ladislaus Lehman, 40 years old, a boarder under the influence of liquor. abstract: LINCOLN never came to regard the army as a more machine, never forgot the individual men who made it up. From the outset, he was the personal friend of every soldier he sent to the front, and somehow every man seemed to know it. No doubt, it was on Lincoln's visits to the camps around Washington, in the early days of the war, that the body of the soldiers get this idea.

abstract: The new Herreshoff car, which is to appear in January, is to be marketed by Harry S. Houpt. abstract: PORT-AU-PRINCE, Dec. 7. -- The proclamation of Gen. Antoine Simon as President of the Haitian Republic has been decided upon. The commander of the victorious army, which drove Nord Alexis from the capital, after a progress around the city, escorted by a body of troops, took possession to-day of the National Palace. He was received at the entrance by Gen. Alphonse, Commandant of the Guard, amid the acclamations of the people and the soldiers.

abstract: WASHINGTON, D.C., Dec. 7. -- The indications are that the Japanese-American entente, designed to protect the territorial integrity of China, will be the subject of a great deal of debate in executive session of the Senate. abstract: The best thing to be said about consecutive instead of universal establishment of two-cent postal rates is that each one which is put in force necessitates another. Thus the German rate is a necessary sequel to the British rate, and it may be assumed that others will follow those two. Nevertheless the Chamber of Commerce has some ground for expressing dissatisfaction with these introductory boons to letter writers, whether on social or commercial topics.

abstract: PARIS, Dec. 7. -- Octavo Mirbeau's comedy, "Le Foyer," which Jules Claretie consented to produce only after a lawsuit, had its first performance at the Comedie Francaise to-night. Its literary quality, the cleverness of several scenes, and a superb interpretation will give the piece what vogue it may have.

abstract: A part of the exhibit of the International Congress on Tuberculosis held lately at Washington, and now displayed here at the Museum of Natural History, is that of the National Jewish Hospital for Consumptives of Denver, Col. abstract: The Hamburg-American liner Kaiserin Augusta Victoria arrived in port yesterday forty-eight hours late after a stormy trip during which two steerage passengers died and were buried at sea and two babies were born. abstract: Supreme Court Justice Hendrick took a positive step late yesterday afternoon to put a stop, as he termed it, to "the awful perjury which is becoming more and more a habit in the civil courts." abstract: PITTSBURG, Dec. 9. -- That Pittsburg religious associations have been caught to the extent of possibly $400,000 by P.J. Kieran and his Fidelity Funding Company is asserted here to-night. This has been a day of great excitement among the clergy and laymen, for many believe they have been absolutely ruined. Charges of forgery and of raising notes are freely made by those who were apparently victimized by Kieran.

abstract: The production of pig iron, according to the compilations of the Iron Age, was the largest during November of any month since the recession set in last Winter, being 1,577,854 gross tons. abstract: ANN ARBOR, Mich., Dec. 9. -- The University of Michigan for the first time in its history will have a rowing crew. Prof. Emil Lorch of the architectural department is already preparing plans for a boat house.

abstract: LONDON, Dec. 5. --"London's gondola," the hansom cab, has had its day, and the future is with the taximotor. What amounts to an official recognition of the fact is to be found in a new police regulation on the subject of cab whistles. Hitherto one blast has signified a call for a hansom, two blasts meant a four wheeler, or "growler," and three were required to summon a taximotor.

abstract: The people of this State five years ago provided for the immediate building of a 1,000-ton barge canal, at a cost of $101,000,000, to replace the old Erie Canal. In these years contracts have been awarded aggregating $35,722,000 in cost, or a little over $7,000,000 a year. At this rate fifteen years would be consumed before the final contracts were let.

abstract: FIVE hundred years ago men painted pictures of biblical scenes as a matter of course. There was nothing else for them to do, if they were to paint at all. abstract: CHEF HIPPOLYTE BONNEFOUX of the Plaza has ideas of his own about carving the National bird. He may not have learned the knack in sunny France; he may even have received some tips from Steward Pike, but nevertheless he can slip a sharp knife between the complicated tendons or through knotty joints with an ease that would make the average paterfamilias green with jealously and drive to despair the inexperienced young husband.

abstract: Secretary WILSON'S statement that the value of the year's harvest is "the most extraordinary total in the Nation's history" does not exhaust its significance. To illustrate, the value of the potato crop is 18 per cent. above any former crop, but the quantity is 5 per cent. below the average.

abstract: Without notice five of the ferry lines connecting Manhattan with Brooklyn via the East River, north of the Brooklyn Bridge, ceased operations at 5 o'clock yesterday morning. The result was one of the biggest tangles in city traffic ever experienced, and at one time the demonstrations of truckmen and passengers on the Brooklyn side reached such proportions that the reserves from two police stations were called out.

abstract: The seizure of the little Venezuelan coast guard ship Alexis by the Dutch cruiser Gelderland was an act of war. The Governor of Curacao, however, declares that "the capture by our war ships of coast guards and war vessels is not to be construed an unfriendly act against the Venezuelans. It is merely a reprisal against CASTRO'S Government, which refuses to give satisfaction for his unfriendly acts toward Holland.''

abstract: PITTSBURG, Penn., Dec. 15. -- The Pennsylvania Railroad has placed an order for fifteen giant locomotives. They are to be hurried from the Juniata shops, in anticipation of a great revival in business, in spite of the fact that the road has many locomotives idle in the shops. It is believed to be the first of a series of moves to provide the entire main line of the Pennsylvania system with heavier locomotives.

abstract: Carrying a sealed message from Mayor Oliver of Toronto, Canada, to Mayor George B. McClellan of this city, T.J. McAughey of Toronto reached Yonkers yesterday afternoon. McAughey covered 763 miles in 7 days and 9 hours, with 15 miles to go to reach City Hall. His previous record for the same distance last August, when he carried a similar message to Mayor McClellan, was 11 days and 20 hours.

abstract: Slow moving in the fog and amid a maze of shipping, incoming and outgoing, the big British freighter Catalone, from Boston, late yesterday afternoon ran down and sank the steamer Daghestan off Sandy Hook, at the entrance to the Gedney Channel. abstract: CONSTANTINOPLE, Dec. 9. -- A curious light is thrown on the complaints that Greeks in Turkey have made to the effect that they were not allowed to vote in the recent Parliamentary elections. abstract: TOLEDO, Ohio, Dec. 19. -- A sensation was sprung to-day in the trial of Don Harvey Hazel, 17, charged with killing his mother, when Mayor Brand Whitlock of Toledo made public an anonymous letter received in his morning mail. abstract: LOS ANGELES, Cal., Dec. 19. -- A new world's record for one mile and a furlong, circular track, was made at Santa Anita Park to-day, when Vox Populi, carrying 110 pounds, won the Golden State Handicap for three-year-olds and upward. He ran the distance in 1:50 flat, which is three-fifths of a second faster than the best previous time, made by Charles Edward at Brighton Beach, N.Y., two years ago.

abstract: Trading in bonds on the New York Stock Exchange, it was learned yesterday, is to be changed from the present "flat" basis to an "and interest" basis. It was said in some quarters that the new way of trading in bonds might be adopted as of Jan. 1 next.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 19. -- There is every prospect of a pretty scramble for the place to be made vacant in March by the elevation of Senator Knox to the portfolio of State in Mr. Taft's Administration. Representatives Dalzell and Burke of Pennsylvania avowed themselves today to be candidates for the toga, while George T. Oliver of Pittsburg, who has been spoken of as Mr. Knox's logical successor, had a long conference with the Senator.

abstract: The repertory for the sixth week of opera at the Metropolitan will include a revival of "L'Elisir d'Amore" and the first performance this season of "Il Trovatore." abstract: New York may awake to-morrow to find itself without a cab service, and possibly without at taxicab service in operation. The indications yesterday were that the 3,000 drivers of cabs and coaches, and possibly the several hundred chauffeurs belonging to the Liberty Dawn Association and the United Teamsters of America will go on strike Monday morning unless their demands for higher wages and recognition of their unions are met by their employers.

abstract: PARIS, Dec. 19. -- The present status of the Steinheil case is somewhat indeterminate, but no one has lost interest in it. For several days it was rumored that no one had any evidence against Mme. Steinheil, and it was quite likely that she would be liberated this week. At present matters seem to have taken a turn where more arrests may be made.

abstract: LONDON, Dec. 19. -- India and Egypt were the subjects of two important contributions to the week's history. In one case Lord Morley, Secretary of State for India, and in the other Lord Cromer, late British plenipotentiary in Egypt, looked far ahead into the future of these great British dependencies, where the leaven of modern political progress is stirring the heavy residues of the civilization of other ages.

abstract: ROANOKE, Va., Dec. 19. -- In a sensational pistol duel on the main street of Wytheville, Va., to-night Chief of Police Walter McClintock and E.A. Cregger were killed. abstract: BERLIN, Dec. 19. -- The statement that the Kaiser has suddenly become a total abstainer, as a fresh evidence of his general "reform," is without foundation. abstract: The Appellate Division seems to have settled finally the case of Jackson vs. Paterno, which a month ago was of great interest to both landlords and tenants. Lawrence S. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Dec. 20. -- James F. Fahnestock, who left the Treasurership of the International Mercantile Marine Company ten days ago to become Assistant Treasurer of the Pennsylvania Railroad, will be the next Treasurer of that company. abstract: MONTCLAIR, N.J., Dec. 20. -- If the weather conditions allow the big bob-sled race at Caldwell will take place on Saturday, Jan. 2. abstract: TRENTON, Dec. 20. -- A hundred of Trenton's poor families were provided with Christmas dinners, fuel, and clothing, and the children of the poor with toys, at the "Christmas Giving" session of the Third Presbyterian Church Sunday School this afternoon. abstract: CROOKHAVEN, Ireland, Dec. 22. -- The British steamer Irada, Capt. Roberts, which sailed from Galveston, Texas, on Dec. 5 for Liverpool, is a total wreck on the southwest point of Mizen Head. Capt. Roberts, a stewardess, and four men were drowned. The remainder of the crew, sixty-five men, were saved.

abstract: Miss Emily Coe, a debutante of the season, had a small dance given for her by her mother, Mrs. Henry E. Coe, at Sherry's last night. abstract: PASADENA, Cal., Dec. 24. -- The great 100-inch glass for the Mount Wilson Solar Observatory is defective. After the first grinding began a large flaw was found so that the casting will have to be thrown away and a new one made. This will delay for many months the construction of the great eight-foot reflecting mirror on the peak.

abstract: WILKESBARRE, Penn., Dec. 24. -- Orders were posted at all the collieries of the Pennsylvania Coal Company and the Hillside Coal and Iron Company to-day for a suspension of work for ten days. abstract: ONE hundred years from tonight no living soul who treads that great White Way will draw from eyries of memory the story of Now. Where are the men of yesterday -- the yesterday of one hundred years? Gone, too, as will be the men of to-day that century hence. But the blood of their blood lives, and the mind of our minds will live anon.

abstract: THE International Congress on Tuberculosis held at Washington in November is, to my mind, the greatest event of the year, because it marks an epoch in the expression of a humanitarian spirit, the spirit of brotherly love. This spirit, combined with the deep thought and profound study which medical men and sociologists the world over have lavished upon the effort to rid the world of this great plague, culminated in the congress.

abstract: LOS ANGELES, Cal., Dec. 26. -- Mme. Lillian Nordica tried to save her Christmas turkey from a fire which damaged somewhat her luxurious private car, the Pilgrim. abstract: The day after Christmas is Boxing Day in England, so called because in the old days it marked the occasion of the actual giving of Christmas boxes. Now it is a national holiday. Besides being the last in the year, it has to suffice Londoners, at all events, until Easter Monday. It's a great day in Cockneyland, and the East End crowds to Hampstead Heath, the picturesque open space in the northwest of London.

abstract: BERLIN, Dec. 26. -- In accordance with usage, expatriated America foregathered for Christmas at the American Woman's Club. abstract: TORONTO, Ont., Dec. 26. -- Tom Longboat, world's champion Marathon runner, and Miss Lauretta Maracie, the Indian school teacher, will not be married by a Protestant Episcopal clergyman in Massey Hall next Monday night, according to programme. abstract: FORT SMITH, Ark., Dec. 28. -- By a decision of the Circuit Court to-day a strip of land twelve miles long and two miles wide, adjoining Fort Smith, becomes "no man's land." abstract: The popularity of the tuberculosis exhibit at the American Museum of Natural History will prove its undoing unless $16,000 is raised at once. abstract: PORT OF SPAIN, Trinidad, Dec. 29. -- There has been fighting at Macuro, on the Venezuelan coast, between adherents of former President Castro and the crew of the gunboat Miranda, working in the interests of the new President, Juan Vicente Gomez. abstract: The Executive Committee of the Republican County Committee gave a dinner to Herbert Parsons, Chairman of the County Committee, at the Republican Club last evening and presented to him a gold-mounted ivory gavel. abstract: A traffic agreement between the Union Pacific and the Kansas City Southern, covering business from Kansas City to the Gulf of Mexico, has been under discussion, it was learned yesterday, between the traffic officials of the two roads. abstract: The Sleillan disaster, in the opinion of Dr. James F. Kemp, Professor of Geology at Columbia University, was caused by a fault developing in the outer crust of the earth's surface in order to allow it to adjust itself to an alteration in the shape of the globe. In this it resembled the San Francisco earthquake, the direction of the force of which may be plainly followed along the Pacific Coast.
